
2620. Counter
Given an integer n, return a counter function. This counter function initially returns n and then returns 1 more than the previous value every subsequent time it is called (n, n + 1, n + 2, etc

/**
 * @param {number} n
 * @return {Function} counter
 */


const createCounter = n => () => n++;  // 



/**
 JS builds an inner function that still “remembers” n.

Every call to that inner function:

Returns the current value of n

Increments it afterward
 */


/** example
 * const counter = createCounter(10)
 * counter() // 10
 * counter() // 11
 * counter() // 12
 */

/**
This question tests your grasp of →

Closures, scope, encapsulation, and function factories — all crucial for callbacks, async handling, and modular JS design.

Time: O(1) per call

Space: O(1) total
*/



